      <h4 class="text-center">Culture</h4>
        <p>Dwarves are a fierce and prideful race, native to Hyraeth’s mountains and mines. They are notoriously trapped between reverence for tradition, and appreciation for adaptability and innovation. They prioritize respect for one another and for the landscape and materials which they utilize. Inherently gifted with metal, stone, and magic, dwarves have long-living clan bonds, dedicated to their kind and their families (either by blood or choice) through even the darkest times. They abide by the idea that with enough ambition and heartiness one can rise to any seat of power, although the old blood that runs throughout the people make this easier to say than do.</p>
      <h5 class="text-center">Religion</h4>
        <p>Many dwarves are faithful servants of Adara or Ryknos, whom they feel represent their kind’s prioritizations of respect, defense, and fairness. It is not uncommon to see dwarves among every god’s faithful, however, for their own clan’s or personal reasonings.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Common Professions</h4>
        <p>Dwarves value career paths based on their level of contribution to society. Craftsmanship and battle prowess come first; battlemages, tacticians, crafters, and fighters are among the most popular and highest-regarded paths among dwarven people. They also hold the Fiol’nolnha, a guild which trains bards and collects Dwarven history, in high regard. Dwarves are generally raised into the profession or professions most common among their family, as having clan elders in their hundreds means easy access to an apprenticeship with a master and upbringings among dozens of experts in a single profession often imparts at least some interest.</p>
      <h5>Metalworking</h5>
        <p>With their innate appreciation of metal and stone, it is no wonder many dwarves have at least some experience in the smithy. Many choose to take on trades of weapon or armor craft, while others prefer fine silvers and golds for jewelry. Regardless of their form, Dwarven metal-crafts hold a certain reputation, and each genuine piece is marked with the iconic interwoven knot engraved into all they forge.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Appearance</h4>
        <h5>Beards & Facial Hair</h5>
          <p>Dwarven beards are rumored to have developed due to their mining origins where those who kept them had a built-in mechanism to filter the dust and grime. In the years since, beards have become symbolic, representing honor and ancestors. Merchants who trade with humans or the Dep’el may prefer sideburns or light scruff in order to better fit in with their connections. no facial hair at all is considered a sign of dishonor.</p>
          <p>Many Dwarven clans keep braided patterns in both their hair and beards. These may be as elaborate as an entire head knotted into a tapestry-like weave, or as simple as several braids corded with colored thread, but are as unique to each Dwarven family as their own name.</p>
        <h5>Clothing</h5>
          <p>Dwarves prefer armor or other clothes with pronounced geometric shapes, such as the facets of gems. Armor or metal garments may bear stones, gems, or even carved ancestral faces.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Structure</h4>
          <p>In societal ranking, all dwarves are assumed worthy of respect until they prove themselves otherwise (although many dwarves are more than happy to explain the difference between respect and acceptance, should need arise); this is not to say that more respect cannot be accumulated, and the actions of one’s ancestors are considered to reflect favorably on their offspring. Contribution is always considered before caste or bloodline, and Thanes assure the people of their worthiness by sacrificing their freedom and independence to serve. Emphasis is put on supporting one’s community through defensive means; and those who pursue careers that may risk their own lives, such as soldiers and battlemages, are considered some of the most honorable within dwarf society.</p>
          <p>Dwarven government is composed of an advisory council, the Vanguard; a representative of the people, the Champion; and an overseer, the Thane.</p>
          <p>The Vanguard is made up of five representatives for trade, labor, war, scholarship and magic, and diplomacy. Appointed to their seats by the ruling Thane upon their taking of the throne, these advisors maintain order at the ground level by reviewing laws and settling petty disputes. Some more radical critics of Khouiel’s government say that the Thane is nothing but a figurehead bound by tradition, while the Vanguard holds the true power and keeps it through bribery and other methods. These claims have been vehemently refuted by the Vanguard itself, but no official action has been taken.</p>
          <p>Chosen through a series of regional competitions, evaluations, and inquiries by the Thane and Vanguard, the Champion is a dwarf of Khouiel or recognized dwarven settlement who can prove that they have made worthy, effective contributions to their people. While in power, the Champion acts as the Thane’s direct representative in diplomatic excursion and in turn represents the Dwarven people in council. A Champion serves for either five or ten years, depending on the Thane’s call. When a Thane dies, all living Champions are called back to Irongate for a week-long tournament process for the Vanguard, the people, and supposedly the gods themselves to determine the next Thane.</p>
          <p>Khouiel’s Thane is seen as the end-all and be-all of law. They are a representative of the people and trusted to do what is best for Khouiel above even their own preferences. Upon their taking of the throne, dwarven clans from across Hyraeth are called to an equal swearing of fealties; where in exchange for bending the knee to the Thane, they in exchange vow to do what is best by the clans, thus establishing the sense of equity and mutual respect that is supposedly built into the core of dwarven leadership. Tradition states that should the Thane ever leave Khouiel, dwarves will fall; as such, the Thane never makes a diplomatic trip beyond the borders of their land.</p>
       <h4 class="text-center">Racial Relations</h4>
        <p>As a general rule of thumb, dwarves are a hearty and friendly enough race that they get along with just about everyone. However, they are also a long-lived species, and in some cases their memory outstretches their kindness.</p>
      <h5>Dep’El</h5>
        <p>The most notable allies of the dwarves are the Dep’El, with whom they have established numerous trade agreements and shared endless projects. Dep’El are permitted into the depths of dwarven mines, where they are welcome to use their talents in order to extract any gems that haven produced. In return, dwarves are given first-pick of the gems mined on Dep’El lands, and the two maintain a short of harmony.</p>
      <h5>Goblins</h5>
        <p>Dwarven clans each have long stories of skirmishes and back-stabbings by Goblins, but these have become infamous for their many contradictions and loose threads. Younger Dwarves tend to treat the Goblins more neutrally, advocating that their elders would be better off focusing on uniting Dwarves rather than fighting about some grave betrayal they can not even remember.</p>
      
      <h4>History</h4>
        <p>Dwarves struggle to record their history, as they didn’t maintain a written language and the long lifespans of their elders meant that oral storytelling has been sufficient in keeping the most notable stories of their people alive. Dwarven clan loyalties and pride mean that many of these stories now have dozens if not hundreds of retellings, some with changes as small as a name pronunciation and others as large as which clans fought for whom in a war. Some contemporary movements to create as truthful a shared narrative as possible have received a mixed reception.</p>
        <p>As far as memory holds, dwarves have always harnessed the resources of the mountains. The oldest songs kept alive recall working deep below the surface, and each range within Khouiel holds its own clan dynamics, many of whom have running feuds over which family has overseen them the longest. It is theorized that once each range, or góra’góradh (literally mountains of the mountains), was run by the head of the largest clan. As these clans merged, made trade, intermarried, and fell, there were fewer and fewer heads, ultimately leading to the first few Thanes of Khouiel. Some of the descendants of these old clans are also said to be the founders of the many guilds in Khouiel and Irongate, including the famous Éguri’s (Smith’s) Union and Adâskei’s (Artificer’s) Union. After the first Thane of Khouiel rose in a supposedly great and glorious battle, they appointed the most notable clans to lead these guilds as a show of respect for their skill. The Temple of Adara and the Temple of Ryknos in Karst Abbey were also established as a means of training honorable children to continue to fight for noble causes.</p>
        <p>The Fiol’nolnha, the order of bardic historians, came about much later, supposedly after a great battle with the goblins that was lost to the tides of time. Since then, they religiously record all political incidents in Dwarven culture. Because Dep’El are also much better record-keepers, dwarves also know that they have been allied with them ever since their exile from El society and helped build not one, but two great cities with their people, one of which had to be abandoned after the Underdark proved too hostile a territory to continue construction.</p>
        <p>Dwarves have been ruled by Thane Seoras for a recorded one-hundred and six years. His rule is notably peaceful, as he prefers diplomatic approaches (particularly ones involving a pint and a barstool) before aggressive ones. He is long-famed for his lengthy negotiations. His Champion, Opyske Axbreak, was appointed within the past two years, and she is rumored to be a far more aloof individual than he. She has spent much of her time on diplomatic travel.</p>  
    </div>
  </div>

