      <h4 class="text-center">Known Settlements</h4>
        <p>Goblins, for the most part, have desired to fit in with the Hyraethian population beyond all else. This has brought them to avoid war and conflict. Due to this, Goblins tend to settle anywhere they can find that is available, or where they won’t feel bad about killing the inhabitants. There are Goblin settlements in numbers too high to count, but those settlements may contain anywhere from 20 Goblins to 200. The settlements tend to not be named and therefore are difficult to keep track of, however Goblins know the names of their own Tribe and the Tribes surrounding them.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Culture</h4>
        <p>Goblin appearance does vary, as any other races would. Despite being a created race, the energies used to make these creatures were chaotic, spurring a great variation of beings. Goblins can be found in all shades of greens. They can have any range of facial features; long or short noses, pronounced chins, and big foreheads, but Goblins always have long pointed ears. They can be tall, short, thin, portly, and in many shapes. The average lifespan for a Goblin is around 50 years. This is also greatly dependent on where a Goblin is from. Goblins who grow up mostly in the cities see slightly longer lifespans. Goblins reach physical maturity anywhere from 12-16 years of age. Goblin gestation periods are only about 4-6 months long. Goblin children are usually born between 4-6 pounds and tend to be born in numbers anywhere from 2 to 6 children. Families of Goblins tend to be exceptionally large, nearing 20 Goblins per family depending on village size.</p>
        <p>Most Goblins are born and raised within a Tribe. Tribes range in size and this often depends on access to land. Tribes are hardly hierarchical, with only three officially recognized figures: Chieftain, Elder, and Ritualist. On some occasions these titles may overlap. The remainder of the Tribe are assigned functions within the village based on their family’s specialty. Families pass down skills to their children, causing them to step into a crucial role as their parents age or the Tribe expands. Major functions within Goblin Tribes tend to be as follows, in no particular order: Hunters, Gatherers, Gardeners, Crafts-person, Healers, Trades-persons, and Herders (the people who care for all of the Goblin children).</p>
        <p>Goblins tend to live in whatever they can muster together. Abandoned villages, poorly cobbled together shacks, and tents are the normal for Goblin architecture. On occasion a village will have especially skilled laborers, and their architecture can resemble buildings of those cultures nearby.</p>
        <p>Goblins do not have a unifying language, as Goblin Tribes are as unique as Goblins themselves. This has caused Goblins across Hyraeth to be well versed in the Common tongue. For the same reasons, Goblins do not have their own written language. Goblins communicate with each other through speech and drawings using descriptors to reference items and ideas. A Goblin who does not know the word for shovel might call it a “dirt spoon,” for example.**As an example, if a Goblin does not know the word for "Shovel", they will refer to it as "the dirt spoon" or similar descriptors. Goblins will speak what often sounds like nonsense with their Tribe members but are generally able to understand the words being said. Sometimes these languages sound like unrestrained shrieking, while others take the form of sign language.</p>
        <p>Although misunderstood as being unintelligent or aggressive, this simply is not the truth. It is true, however, that Goblins lack strong language skills, writing skills, and emotional coping mechanisms, all leading to this misconception. What Goblins lack in communication and interpersonal skills, they make up for with a knack for creating trinkets and inventions, an unending pursuit to be happy, and a desire to be better than they were the day before. This does not mean that setbacks or obstacles will not send them into a fury, but this also does not guarantee it. They have as many feelings and emotions as any other race in Hyraeth.</p>
        <p>Goblins tend to be traders and craftsmen and are both spending large amounts of time within their Tribes and experiencing life among other races. This constant change in community causes Goblins to learn about the world around them more slowly, often going back to Goblin ways of living as soon as they return home. Once this happens, Goblins tend to forget the social lessons learned while living among the other races. Those who stay strictly to the lands of the Tribe tend to rarely wander into civilization. The perception is that they are unwelcome, and this fact often causes Goblins to feel like outcasts. All of these reasons contribute to the perception of Goblins as rude, inconsiderate, or stupid. However, Goblins care deeply for their Tribes and their friends. People of other races able to befriend a Goblin find themselves a loyal and reliable friend and ally.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Racial Relations</h4>
        <h5>Dwarves</h5>
          <p>When Goblins first immigrated down to Hyraeth, a portion of them settled around Irongate and Crym’s Peak. To this day it is unknown, but something happened between the Goblins and the Dwarves, and they have had strained relationships ever since. Most Dwarves are raised to dislike Goblins, and the story tends to change with each Clan and generation. Goblins, on the other hand, are always bewildered when a Dwarf shows them disrespect.</p>
        <h5>Dale Elves</h5>
          <p>On occasion Goblin Tribes may settle in places of Dale Elf control. In most cases this is no issue, as Goblins are willing to work with the Dale Elves, but in some cases the Dale Elves are offended or may feel pushed out.</p>
        <h5>Deep Elves</h5>
          <p>In the many Goblin attempts to be a part of Hyraeth, they did not often attempt to settle Tribes in the Underdark. On occasion a Tribe may settle near a Dep’El settlement, but there has never been strife.</p>
        <h5>High Elves</h5>
          <p>Knowing Goblins have tried their best to acclimate to a strange and different world, the Eldar’El have grown to pity the Goblins, albeit respecting the work they have put in.</p>
        <h5>Human</h5>
          <p>Human and Goblin relationships vary heavily from region to region. Overall, each race tolerates each other, nothing more. Personal relationships may be found but Human governments are not often engaging in Goblin “politics”.</p>
        <h5>Sukh</h5>
          <p>Sukh, being heavy traders, often rely on Goblin cleverness and ingenuity to enhance the experience of a caravan journey. Sukh and Goblins are often found making business deals and on rare occasions a Sukh may take an abnormally polite Goblins invitation to spend the night at their village as an honored guest.</p>
        <h5>Wildren</h5>
          <p>Wildren’s large capacity for empathy has caused Goblins to often gravitate towards this race. Goblins put a large amount of trust in Wildren due to their ability to be kind and understanding. They often live closely with one another and engage in important local trading.</p>
      <h4>History</h4>
        <p>Goblins came about, ages ago, during the time of The Sorcerium. In preparation for a great war, the Goblins were a creation of pure hate, so that The Sorcerium may know victory. The Goblins fought for this council of Sorcerers for many years, pressing forth, fighting a never-ending war. As time went on it became apparent to The Sorcerium that they had made a fatal error. They could not foresee that beings driven by pure emotion cannot exist. The Goblins began to realize that they could not hate without love. Their anger could not be fueled without joy and their vitriol could not be spewed without pride. Unrest among the armies of Goblins grew, and The Sorcerium began to lose control.</p>
        <p>In the end, The Sorcerium fell to the swords of their enemies, the Goblins leaving them to their fates to seek out new lives. However, this story does not have a happy ending. Though Goblins began to learn the great expanse of emotions, they continued to default to hate in times of challenge and stress. They found that compared to other races they met, they were slow to learn and difficult to communicate with. These frustrations became anger, and they grew to have a nasty reputation. As the Goblins traveled south, they split off into many factions. Across Hyraeth Goblins built up their tribes, direly seeking a place to call home. Over the many years of their expansion, the locals around them grew to trust them, understanding Goblin way of life, and Goblin flaws. The compassion of Hyraethians is unconditional and the Goblin race continues to grow and expand, becoming more advanced and accepted as their time spent with their neighbors grows. They have made many friends and allies and have learned a great deal about the world, even if it takes them a little longer than everyone else.</p>  
    </div>
