      <h4 class="text-center">Culture</h4>
        <h5>Acceptance & Attitudes</h5>
          <p>Half-elves are often raised with one side of their family and are as steeped in that culture as possible. Their exposure to religion, understanding of history, political affiliations, and fundamental values will then all be in line with whichever race this happens to be.</p>
        <h5>Dale Elves</h5>
          <p>As a child of the natural world, half Dale elves may find a home among their elven kin. Dale Elves have never placed legal restrictions on their halved offspring, and some families even take in the human parent. Even those who do not take this step often encourage communications between the child and their other family. However, half-elves may experience pressure from their family or clan to help bridge the political gap between humans and elves, and furthermore may still experience discrimination or prejudice from full elves who feel they are not as deserving of their people’s resources.</p>
        <h5>Deep Elves</h5>
          <p>Ever stringent, Deep Elves consider reproducing with a human a sign of low self-esteem among elves. An elf who dares to bring back the offspring of this relationship is held in lower regard and exiled or otherwise punished by their House. The child is then often fostered, adopted, or raised by extended family. They are permitted no knowledge or contact with their human side. Furthermore, they are banned by law from reproducing and highly discouraged from marrying. They are only suitable for menial or simple occupations. The highest a half Deep Elf might strive for among their elven kin would be the position of Royal Jester.</p>
        <h5>High Elves</h5>
          <p>The Eldar’El have maintained a balance of approaches. The child and parent are not openly rejected, although it is not uncommon for the extended family to either give the child away for fostering or quietly disown the parent. The child is permitted knowledge of its human family and allowed to contact them for research purposes as they grow older, so long as the other side is receptive. However, these offspring are considered somewhat weaker than their full-elf counterparts, and are often encouraged to pursue careers in simple labor, religion, or lower levels of scholarship. They are not considered suitable for high academic or military-level work and may be somewhat smothered.</p>
        <h5>Humans</h5>
          <p>Human families are not always thrilled by the appearance of a half-elf child, but have not often strictly prohibited or limited their existence, and they are still considered far more accepting than any of the elven people. Noble and common folk families tend to treat the child as any other born out of wedlock (assuming the parents did not marry); they may send them away for fostering or education, may not tell them of their origins until they are old enough to notice physical differences, or keep it isolated until adulthood. Commonfolk are more likely to accept the elven parent should they be in need of a new home. However, those with prejudices may be more inclined to try and encourage the child to be as human as possible and attempt to reject their elven origins entirely.</p>
      <h4>A Pattern in Personality</h4>
        <p>Split between two worlds, neither of which they fit perfectly into, half-elves tend to develop a strong sense of independence and individualism—although it’s worth noting not every half-elf is truly rejected. In more restrictive situations, some overcompensate, earning further rejection in the process. Others still turn to acts of rebellion as comfort, no matter how small. This may take the form of physical alterations as small as unique piercings to actions as big as openly embracing the culture of one parent to spite the other. Even the most positive from the most accepting families encounter hurdles or prejudice due to their heritage, and it is difficult for them not to become jaded by repeated rejection. More still come to embrace and highlight their individuality: they will never fit in to begin with, so why not embrace it?</p>
        <p>However they express it, half-elves are always different. By choice or force they often become outcasts, pursuing some sense of community where it seems none exists for them.</p>
      <h4>Names</h4>
        <p>Often given names of one of their parents’ cultures (although some are kinder than others), it isn’t unusual for a half-elf to ultimately choose their own. They may take one of a mentor who has been warmer to them than their kin, or of an object they have sentiment towards, or a value they wish to embody. Most families refuse these names, writing them off as the whim of a child who couldn’t know better. It is thus more common for the half-elf to use them once they leave home, hoping to shed behind their often divided upbringings.</p>
      <h4>Professions & Pursuits</h4>
        <p>Some half-elves pick up ancestral or traditional skills in the hope if they succeed in becoming experts at what their people value most, they will be better accepted. This may look like an artificing half Deep Elf, or yet another smith in a human family of smiths. But it is difficult for them to find work in these fields, as competition is high even for their full-blooded peers and if their heritage is known, it provides yet another disadvantage. They often have to move elsewhere in order to find a profession, defeating their original purpose.</p>
        <p>Others decide to forge their own paths early on, pursuing lives as travelling minstrels or thieves. These are often the same half-elves that used magnificent daydreams to escape their less-ideal upbringings, making themselves out as a criminal mastermind or famed storyteller in the making. Not everyone can rise to glory, though, and they usually fall in with common thieves and tavern bards like the rest.</p>
        <p>However they get there, many half-elves will settle into professions that allow them flexibility and travel. The less relevant appearance, the better. If there is the promise of a tight-knit community that allows them a sense of freedom, such as an adventurers’ or thieves’ guild, then they are all the better for it.</p>
    </div>
