  <div class="row">
    <div class="container col-12" id="HighElvesDetails">
      <h4 class="text-center">Scholarship</h4>
        <p>Many, many centuries ago, the Eldar’El’s first forays into scholarly pursuits were fueled by the desire to regain the powers of their Fae ancestors. Eldar’El researched potential Fae weaknesses, the terms of their deals, the limits of their power, and any other path they thought might grant them an upper hand. They were an ambitious, unstoppable people, united by a common goal; but in time their camaraderie began to fray, and the El turned on one another (not for the last time).The crimes committed in this tumultuous time gave way to the Ancient Council, a group of Eldar’El who saw the chance for their people to reunite - this time guided by a shared code. Through their efforts, the first Laws of the Eldar’El were established and their research focuses turned from solely the Fae. Now, many Eldar’El have their own individual motivations for research, fueled by that same passion to understand that drove the Eldar’El in the very beginning.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Religion</h4>
        <p>Deities worshiped most by Eldar’El are Amitel, God of the Aether, and twins Adara and Naenya, sun and moon, who are depicted as Elves themselves.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Holidays</h4>
        <p>The Eldar’El treat seasonal holidays with the utmost respect. They are a time for gathering and celebration. The Eldar’El will host gatherings that range from feasts with entertainment to formal and costume balls. Holidays are not quite the same in Eldar’El society as in others. Instead of purely religious, times such as Midwinter, Midsummer, and Hallowtide are celebrated by lavish balls or festivals. These balls have various ancient themes and rules that are followed with pride. (As does everything with the Eldar’El.) </p>
        <h5>Midwinter Gathering</h5>
          <p>Midwinter Gathering is goddess Adara’s time. It marks the turning point in the cold season, when the light returns to the land. Celebration of this holiday tends to be casual.  Detailed logistics can be difficult to arrange this time of year; thus, festivities tend to be more laid back than most. This gathering is often considered more joyous than Naenya’s feast, though Eldar’El are very careful to consider both sisters equally.</p>
        <h5>Springtide Celebration</h5>
          <p>Springtide Celebration is a relaxed, yet somewhat formal holiday. It celebrates the shedding of the winter cold into the light air of spring. Wearing of new clothing or other adornment is very popular to help emphasize the rebirth of the year.</p>
        <h5>Midsummer Festival</h5>
          <p>Midsummer Festival is the time of courtship and celebration of love. Though the Eldar’El refrain from expressing emotion, they still take the time to appreciate and experience them. Oftentimes gifts or displays of jewelry, poetry, or magic are shared with their beloved or desired romantic interest. Elaborate masquerades are arranged to pair potential partners.</p>
        <h5>Aventine</h5>
          <p>Aventine is unlike the other holidays as it is more of a time of year. It is the time to celebrate the harvest and finalize preparations for the lean times. The Eldar’El acknowledge this holiday by hosting smaller feasts to recognize visiting travelers and merchants who do not often come to their lands.</p>
        <h5>Hallowtide Ball</h5>
          <p>Hallowtide Ball is traditionally costumed, the intent to hide your identity. The Eldar’El allow themselves this holiday to relax some of their cultural restrictions. A little mischief seems to happen during the celebration of Hallowtide, but rarely do the perpetrators ever get revealed.</p>
        <h5>The Feast of the Waning Moon</h5>
          <p>The Feast of the Waning Moon is known as the goddess Naenya’s time. It marks the arrival of winter. Pragmatism was once necessary for surviving the harsh season. Though this is no longer the case, the feast is still celebrated in the same fashion. A touch of melancholy can be felt this time of year. The time for preparations to survive the lean times has passed, and everyone knows it will be awhile before the Midwinter Gathering arrives.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Appearance</h4>
        <p>An Eldar’El is raised from birth to be well spoken, distinguished, and honorable. While an Eldar’El will never tell you a lie, they may not tell you the whole truth either. They are very strategic and meticulous in everything they do.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Structure</h4>
        <p>Like all Elves, the Eldar’El have an unmatched eye for beauty in all its forms. Music, art, poetry, dance, and even some forms of martial arts are highly respected and refined in Eldar’El society. There are many rules as to how an Eldar’El should and shouldn’t act. There are decidedly less rules governing general morality. The law itself and one’s ability to justify one’s actions within the letter of the law is more important than vague morality for its own sake. Eldar’El are not as emotionally attuned as their brethren and can seem cold and aloof by comparison. This is thought to be an example of their connection to the ancestral Fairy-Folk.  Being a race quite literally born of the union of Fae and the Aether, wizards and enchanting are the backbone of Eldar’El society. They are the most common class, though not every Eldar’El is one, and skilled and knowledgeable wizards are the most respected members of society.</p>
        <p>Though fighters are recognized as essential, paladins are considered more highly than the commonfighter. A paladin’s oath and binding sense of justice closely mirrors those same values in Eldar’El society.</p>
        <p>One thing that seems surprising to other races is that bards are respected and deemed as essential in Eldar’El society. Beauty and its appreciation are essential to Eldar’El life, and music, poetry,  and storytelling are the most common ways to pursue and appreciate the beauty of life.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Government and Economy</h4>
        <p>The Wise Council is the ruling body of all Eldar’El society. Its seven members are elected to their positions, and they provide every law, structure, decree, and major decision that will affect High Elves. Their word is absolute and highly respected. The Wise Council does allow for audiences when any member of society feels strongly about an issue, however the quality, length, and time of this audience is granted based on how much worth the individual can prove based on their accomplishments and reputation in society. Governance is considered the arms of the Wise Council. They are individuals trusted and elected by the Council’s judgment to handle affairs on a smaller scale within communities and towns.</p>
        <p>Masterwork Enchantments are the hallmark of the Eldar’El. No other race has such a connection- or obsession- with the Aether as what is literally in the blood of these Elves. Uncounted generations of Eldar’El have spent their entire long lives in the pursuit of the perfection of this craft, and it is said that a Master Eldar’El enchanter can enchant just about any object to DO anything.</p>
        <p>One other specialty that can only be found with an Eldar’El is the delicate and rare beauty of sea silk. Harvested by a secret process in Siren’s Song Bay, it is the softest and most luxurious silk found in the entire kingdom. Priority on obtaining the material is given to High Elf craftsmen, but its quality is such that you may find those in every region willing to give the coin to obtain it.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Racial Relations</h4>
        <h5>Dael’El</h5>
          <p>The Dale Elves are technically, by blood, the same as the High Elves. Both societies recognize this and often put aside their other differences for the sake of family. These Elves will often greet each other as “cousin”, even if they are strangers. The Eldar’El think of their woods-dwelling cousins as like children; rowdy, unrefined, and impatient. They still are family though, and Eldar’El do their best to help their silly cousins. However, the Eldar’El respect the Dael’El’s autonomy, and have never seriously stuck a hand into any matter they believe to be primarily a Dael’El problem. For this reason and few others, no serious discontent has ever arisen between the two groups.</p>
        <h5>Dep’El</h5>
          <p>Deep Elves are another matter entirely. Dale Elves will not speak to one directly, often leaving High Elves to mediate. The Eldar’El have no quarrel personally with the Dep’El. However, their original exile being a matter of serious infraction of the law Eldar’El, find their presence to be somewhat distasteful. Dep’El are not seen as inherently evil, only as lawbreakers and untrustworthy. An Eldar’El would never be blatantly rude to another. So despite how little they have in common and how much they disagree, relations between the two remain amiable.</p>
        <h5>Wildren</h5>
          <p>Though Dael’El seem to be somewhat obsessed with Wildren, Eldar’El retain a healthy respect. Wildren are also born of a kind of Fae, and so despite having nothing else in common, there is a kind of kinship of ancestry felt.</p>
        <h5>Dwarves</h5>
          <p>Dwarves are seen as dependable and useful allies, given their skill sets are different yet complementary to High Elves. Relations are not always smooth sailing, though there has never been any iconic feuds between these races in known history.</p>
        <h5>Humans</h5>
          <p>Humans are fascinating and somewhat dangerous. Unlike any other race, and so short lived, their attitudes and cultures are often quite different than the Eldar’El. Being so short lived allows for quick evolution, and sometimes the Humans’ culture even varies greatly within themselves. Humans make marvelous material for studying.</p>
        <h5>Half Elves</h5>
          <p>Half Elves are not as interesting as Humans, as they are not as suitable as research material and nor are truly Elves. They are not quite as respected as a full-blooded Elf, though they are considered to belong to their Elven parent’s clan. It is very rare for the Elvish parent of a Half Elf to be an Eldar’El.</p>
        <h5>Sukh</h5>
          <p>The Sukh are not very well known to the Eldar’El yet. Though trade routes have been established to Elven lands since ancient times, a comprehensive study of their race has not yet been accomplished and so an official opinion on their race as a whole cannot yet be reached.</p>
        <h5>Goblins</h5>
          <p>Goblins are looked upon by the Eldar’El with pity for their unfortunate existence. Though others often dislike Goblins and will not hesitate to perform violent acts upon them, an Eldar’El does not hate and will not act unjustly against one. Goblins are exploited, miserable, and ugly to boot. They are not really seen as a true race and more as a construct. This is currently a subject of philosophical debate among the Wise Council- what truly makes any race “real” and not merely a construct of some form of magic or circumstance? - but until an answer is reached an Eldar’El will not truly respect a Goblin.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">History</h4>
      <p>All Elves share a common ancestry in the legendary fairy-folk. But none keep their history quite so meticulously as the Eldar’El. Many have forgotten, but the Eldar’El are the closest to their ancestors. The Eldar’El records shed a (mostly) subjective light on the somewhat mythological origins of Elven kind. The fairy-folk witnessed the birth of a new realm from behind the veil of their own world. Curious, they crossed the veil for the first time. Before the age of man, before dwarves first emerged from underground, the fairy-folk danced on unspoiled earth and wove pure and potent magics. The breath of creation still fresh in this new world enchanted some of the members of the fairy-folk, and as their brethren returned across the veil, these few stayed. The fairy-folk’s blood danced with the rhythm of the magic in this world, and the more magic they did, the more permanently linked to the earth they became. As this world evolved and grew, the fairy-folk evolved and grew. In many ages, they became the Elves. These Elves were of one race, one clan. As other races emerged in this world, the Elves remained as they were- scholars, observers, mages, and cultivators of beauty. Over time, some Elves were not happy with their roles. They rejected such clean-cut finery, the pomp and circumstance, and relentless studying. These restless children eventually gained permission to forever leave the cities and settlements of those they would come to call the Eldar’El, and the Dael’El were born.</p>
      <p>The beginning of the New Age is shrouded in mystery. Even the extensive Eldar’El records tout embarrassing gaps in these ancient times. We do know that in the thirteenth Winter after the war, a new Dael’El leader, Arbeli the Maelstrom, sought to dramatically expand his territory to create a buffer between Dael’El lands and the young and aggressive Humans. This land he sought to acquire was the homeland of Wildren; his reckless ambition sparked conflict between Dael’El and Wildren, Dael’El and Humans, and civil unrest amongst the Dael’El themselves. The Eldar’El Wise Council sought to advise Arbeli against his foolish actions, but he chose not to listen. The Eldar’El do not directly meddle in the affairs of other races, and so because the Eldar’El themselves were not threatened; it was deemed that there was no other action to be taken with Arbeli.  The unrest in the land, however, did threaten Eldar’El- and so they instead sought to mediate peace talks with Humans and Wildren on the behalf of the Dael’El. Arbeli repeatedly broke his word on the agreements reached in these talks and so the Eldar’El rescinded any responsibility for their independent cousins’ actions, refusing any aid until Arbeli would repent for his actions, make peace with the other races, and step down as the ruler of the Dael’El. Some within the Dael’El thought these actions were not enough, and forever changed history with the assassination of Arbeli the Malestrom. Though the leader taking Arbeli’s place followed the suggestions of the Wise Council and was able to make amends with the other races, the assassination itself was stillseen as a forbidden act, and those responsible and who supported it were cast out. Finding no forgiveness with either of their brethren, they became the Dep’El.</p>  
    </div>
  </div>

