      <h4 class="text-center">Culture</h4>
      <h5>From Nomadic Origins to Empire</h5>
        <p>As nomads, having first lived amongst the other races with no homeland of their own, the Human race represents an amalgamation of many cultures. Everything from architecture to agriculture reflects the influence of the elder races from where the first Human settlers set down their roots. With no apparent base cultural influence, Humans have borrowed from Hyraeth’s other cultures; Dwarven looking temples and keeps, wrought in stone in defiance of the wooded terrain. Homes and shops built in the styles of the Dael’El to blend into the landscape to give them a pleasing natural look. “This is the way it has always been done,” is not an answer most Humans are willing to accept. They will happily learn anything someone is willing to teach them, but once the lesson is over they take ownership of it. Generally this means experimenting to find ways to improve upon it. Be it art, craft, or magic, Humans find ways to take things further than anyone else would have imagined. Humans their lives in a manner to best suited to blend in with the kingdoms they call home, wherever it may be. While it is rare these days to find a nomadic tribe, it is quite common for Humans to cluster in small villages and hamlets as many of the Human race prefer a more fringe lifestyle similar to the Wildren than packed in together in sprawling cities like the Eldar’El. This does not mean that Humans will not gather in cities as many do, particularly in places like the Attercup Domain and Kingdom of Cantara.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">Racial Relations</h4>
        <h5>Dwarves</h5>
          <p>They are gruff, short tempered, sometimes rude to a fault, but their skill with metals and stonecraft is unsurpassed. We've learned a lot about stone and steel craft from them. Even managed to impress some of them enough to build that joint settlement where they're making even more advancements in smithing. If you find yourself in a tight situation, you can trust one of them to have your back.</p>
        <h5>Dale Elves</h5>
          <p>While the High Elves still treat us like children, at least their Dale cousins are willing to work with us. A little too militaristic in their worship of the Storm Lord? Perhaps. But their followers of Enoon are sociable enough. It doesn't hurt that they're helping us gain a better understanding of the Wildren and why they seem to hate us.</p>
        <h5>Deep Elves</h5>
          <p>The deep elves are an odd bunch. High Elves walk around with a stick up their backside, acting like their dirt does not stink, but at least you always know where you stand with them. The Dep’El causes many Humans to have an uneasy feeling. Something about them just is not right. I would say it has to do with them living underground, but the dwarves do not give Humans the creeps like these guys do. All that whispering and looking like they are trying to decide if they should kill you or just ignore you.</p>
        <h5>Goblins</h5>
          <p>Human and Goblin relationships vary heavily from region to region. Overall each race tolerates each other, nothing more. Personal relationships may be found but Human governments are not often engaging in Goblin “politics”.</p>
        <h5>High Elves</h5>
          <p>The living conditions under the High Elves were not so bad. Sure they looked down on us, treated Humans like pets, but then, they do that to everyone. They are helpful in the political arena though, so long as you are careful and do not let them sneak in things that benefit only them. They have been helpful in making sure people from the Freelands do not cross over our borders.</p>
        <h5>Half Elves</h5>
          <p>You almost cannot help but to feel bad for these half breeds. The elves reject them as being too Human. If they do not have facial hair, we group them in with the elves. Worse, if they do have facial hair we tend to group them in with us. It is not unheard of to encounter a Human with pointy ears after all.</p>
        <h5>Sukh</h5>
          <p>Shrewd and difficult traders, these cats are! Follow these two rules and you will be fine. Oh! And never sit down to make a deal with them if you have been drinking. You will wind up with more than you needed and a lot less coin to count. I am not trying to say that all of them will take advantage of you, but they do love winning.</p>
        <h5>Wildren</h5>
          <p>I am still not sure what their deal is. Strong connection to the fae and the forests is what I hear. It explains why they seem a little off and are constantly wrapping themselves around trees. I also hear that they hate us for “exploiting” the forests and animals. Well, not all of us can live off moss and grass.</p>
      <h4 class="text-center">History</h4>
        <p>The origins of Humankind are unclear. It is only over the last several centuries that they have learned to keep written records. Many songs and tales in the oral tradition tell of lengthy migrations, oppression and war. It is surmised that the Human capacity of defiance originates with a time of subjugation that they faced in the far-flung past. Tribal and migratory for most of their collective memory, hunting and gathering became an artform to Humans and as they encountered other races they would add bits of their technology and culture to their own. This led to a massive range of tribal differences that have all gone different directions. The Attercup Domain is the first of the settled human lands that grew into a Domain of independent city-states and villages. Others took to sailing the vast interior and exterior seas of Hyraeth, while others stretched out west further and further until there were clashes with some of the natives. </p>  
